type="user">jms-00YG</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00YG.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Forester 4.2 › first-class functions and lazy arguments › combining fluid bindings and lazy arguments"><fr:link
href="jms-00YF.xml"
title="Forester 4.2 › first-class functions and lazy arguments"
addr="jms-00YF"
type="local"><fr:link
href="jms-00WK.xml"
title="Forester 4.2"
addr="jms-00WK"
type="local">Forester 4.2</fr:link> › first-class functions and lazy arguments</fr:link> › combining fluid bindings and lazy arguments</fr:title><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:link
href="jms-00RH.xml"
title="Forester 4.0 › enhanced XML support"
addr="jms-00RH"
type="local">Forester 4.0’s enhanced XML support</fr:link> makes it possible (see <fr:link
href="jms-00RL.xml"
title="Forester 4.0 › enhanced XML support › emitting XML and resolving namespaces › a worked example"
addr="jms-00RL"
type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number
addr="jms-00RL" /></fr:link>) to write <fr:link
href="jms-00YE.xml"
title="MathML"
addr="jms-00YE"
type="local">MathML</fr:link> directly as an alternative to using <fr:link
href="jms-005P.xml"
title="Forester"
addr="jms-005P"
type="local">Forester</fr:link>’s TeX-like math mode via KaTeX. For example, we can write the following wrappers for some basic <fr:link
href="jms-00YE.xml"
title="MathML"
addr="jms-00YE"
type="local">MathML</fr:link> elements:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\xmlns:mml{http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML}
\def\math[body]{\<mml:math>{\body}}
\def\mrow[body]{\<mml:mrow>{\body}}
\def\mi[x]{\<mml:mi>{\x}}
\def\mo[o]{\<mml:mo>{\o}}
\def\mn[n]{\<mml:mn>{\n}}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>With this in hand, we can write prose involving <fr:link
href="jms-00YE.xml"
title="MathML"
addr="jms-00YE"
type="local">MathML</fr:link> content, like so:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\p{Let \math{\mi{x}} and \math{\mi{y}} be integers such that \math{\mrow{\mrow{\mi{x}\mo{-}\mi{y}}\mo{=}\mn{0}}}.}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>The above is a bit messy. We can clean it up with some function definitions:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\plus[x][y]{\mrow{\x \mo{+} \y}}
\def\equals[x][y]{\mrow{\x \mo{=} \y}}
\let\x{\mi{x}}
\let\y{\mi{y}}

\p{Let \math{\x} and \math{\y} be integers such that \math{\equals{\plus{\x}{\y}}{\mn{0}}}.}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>It is annoying that we have to always wrap things in <fr:code><![CDATA[\math]]></fr:code>. By combining first-class functions, lazy arguments, and fluid bindings, we can lift this requirement:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[% Allocate a fluid binding to hold the function that enters math mode.
\alloc\math-wrapper

% Ensure that a given (lazy) argument is evaluated inside a
% <mml:math> element.
\def\ensure-math[~body]{%
 \scope{%
  % Set a default value for \math-wrapper (no-op if already set).
  \put?\math-wrapper{\fun[x]{\<mml:math>{\x}}}%
  %
  % Apply the current function bound to \math-wrapper.
  \get\math-wrapper{%
   % Bind \math-wrapper to the identity function in the current scope so that
   % we do not get redundant <mml:math> nodes.
   \put\math-wrapper{\fun[x]{\x}}%
   %
   % Force the \body thunk to evaluate the body within the wrapper.
   \body{}%
  }%
 }%
}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>We now re-define our macro library to use the <fr:code><![CDATA[\ensure-math]]></fr:code>:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\def\mrow[~x]{\ensure-math{\<mml:mrow>{\x{}}}}
\def\mi[~x]{\ensure-math{\<mml:mi>{\x{}}}}
\def\mo[~x]{\ensure-math{\<mml:mo>{\x{}}}}
\def\mn[~x]{\ensure-math{\<mml:mn>{\x{}}}}
\def\plus[~x][~y]{\mrow{\x{} \mo{+} \y{}}}
\def\equals[~x][~y]{\mrow{\x{} \mo{=} \y{}}}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>Now, we can put <fr:link
href="jms-00YE.xml"
title="MathML"
addr="jms-00YE"
type="local">MathML</fr:link> content freely into prose without needing to wrap it each time.</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\let\x{\mi{x}}
\let\y{\mi{y}}

\p{Let \x and \y be integers such that \equals{\plus{\x}{\y}}{\mn{0}}.}]]></fr:pre></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
